=== TLS Connection Example ===

TLS provides encrypted network connections.

1. Connect to a TLS server:
   result <- Tls.connect hostname port

2. Send bytes:
   _ <- Tls.sendBytes conn (Bytes.fromList [...])

3. Receive bytes (up to N):
   response <- Tls.recvBytes conn 1024

4. Close connection:
   Tls.close conn

=== Type Signatures ===
connect : String -> Int -> IO (Result Error TlsConn)
sendBytes : TlsConn -> Bytes -> IO (Result Error Unit)
recvBytes : TlsConn -> Int -> IO (Result Error Bytes)
close : TlsConn -> IO (Result Error Unit)

=== Example: Simple HTTPS Request ===
-- Connect to example.com over TLS
result <- Tls.connect "example.com" 443
case result of
  Err e -> IO.println "Connection failed"
  Ok conn ->
    do
      -- Send HTTP GET request
      let request = "GET / HTTP/1.1\r\nHost: example.com\r\n\r\n"
      _ <- Tls.sendBytes conn (stringToBytes request)
      -- Read response
      response <- Tls.recvBytes conn 4096
      -- Close
      Tls.close conn

=== Use Case: PostgreSQL Protocol ===
The PostgreSQL wire protocol can be implemented using:
- Tls.connect for SSL connections
- Bytes.packInt32BE for message lengths
- Bytes.packInt16BE for field counts
- Pure Lune functions for protocol encoding/decoding

